==Old English==
===Etymology===
Germanic ''*miluk-'', from Indo-European ''*h₂melg̑-''.

''Germanic cognates:'' Old Frisian [[melok]], Old Saxon [[miluk]] (Dutch [[melk]]), Old High German [[miluh]] (German [[Milch]]), Old Norse [[mjólk]] (Swedish [[mjölk]]), Gothic [[𐌼𐌹𐌻𐌿𐌺𐍃]].

''Indo-European cognates:'' Latin [[mulgere|mulgēre]], Greek [[αμελγειν]], Russian [[молозиво]], Lithuanian [[melžti|mélžti]], Welsh [[blith]], Tocharian A ''malke''.

